Add search/filter state to the Zustand issuesStore and build the search input UI in IssuesSection with debounced filtering.

## Store Changes (apps/desktop/src/stores/issuesStore.ts)

1. Add new state fields to `IssuesState`:
   - `searchQuery: string` (default: `''`) -- the debounced/committed search text used for filtering

2. Add new actions to `IssuesActions`:
   - `setSearchQuery: (query: string) => void` -- sets the search query

3. Add a **derived selector function** (exported, not in the store) that filters issues:
   ```typescript
   export function filterIssuesBySearch(issues: GitHubIssue[], query: string): GitHubIssue[] {
     if (!query.trim()) return issues;
     const lowerQuery = query.toLowerCase();
     return issues.filter((issue) => {
       const titleMatch = issue.title.toLowerCase().includes(lowerQuery);
       const bodyMatch = issue.body?.toLowerCase().includes(lowerQuery) ?? false;
       const labelMatch = issue.labels.some((label) =>
         label.name.toLowerCase().includes(lowerQuery)
       );
       return titleMatch || bodyMatch || labelMatch;
     });
   }
   ```

4. Update the initial state to include `searchQuery: ''`.

5. Update `apps/desktop/src/stores/index.ts` to also export `filterIssuesBySearch`.

## IssuesSection Component Changes (apps/desktop/src/components/sidebar/IssuesSection.tsx)

1. Add local state for the **immediate** input value: `const [searchInput, setSearchInput] = useState('')`

2. Read the committed search query from the store: `const searchQuery = useIssuesStore((s) => s.searchQuery)`
   Read the setter: `const setSearchQuery = useIssuesStore((s) => s.setSearchQuery)`

3. Import `filterIssuesBySearch` from the store.

4. Add a debounce effect that syncs `searchInput` to the store after 300ms:
   ```typescript
   useEffect(() => {
     const timer = setTimeout(() => {
       setSearchQuery(searchInput);
     }, 300);
     return () => clearTimeout(timer);
   }, [searchInput, setSearchQuery]);
   ```

5. Compute filtered issues using useMemo:
   ```typescript
   const filteredIssues = useMemo(
     () => filterIssuesBySearch(issues, searchQuery),
     [issues, searchQuery]
   );
   ```

6. Add the search input row in the JSX, immediately after the `{headerActions}` block and before the error/loading/empty states. The search input row includes:
   - A text input with placeholder "Search issues..." and value bound to `searchInput`
   - A clear button (x) that is only visible when `searchInput` is non-empty. Clicking it sets `searchInput` to `''` and also immediately calls `setSearchQuery('')` to bypass the debounce for instant clear.
   - A match count span displayed when `searchQuery` is non-empty, showing e.g. "5 of 12" (filteredIssues.length of issues.length)

   Structure:
   ```tsx
   <div className="issues-section-search">
     <input
       type="text"
       className="issues-section-search-input"
       placeholder="Search issues..."
       value={searchInput}
       onChange={(e) => setSearchInput(e.target.value)}
       disabled={!hasProject}
     />
     {searchInput && (
       <button
         className="issues-section-search-clear"
         onClick={() => { setSearchInput(''); setSearchQuery(''); }}
         type="button"
         aria-label="Clear search"
       >
         &times;
       </button>
     )}
     {searchQuery && (
       <span className="issues-section-search-count">
         {filteredIssues.length} of {issues.length}
       </span>
     )}
   </div>
   ```

7. Replace all references to `issues` in the rendering section with `filteredIssues`:
   - The `.issues-section-list` map: `filteredIssues.map((issue) => ...)`
   - The empty state condition: update to check `filteredIssues.length === 0` but also handle the case where there ARE issues but the search filtered them all out (show "No matching issues" instead of "No issues found")
   - The badge count on CollapsibleSection: keep using `issues.length` for the total badge, so users always see the total count

8. Update the empty state logic to distinguish between "no issues at all" and "no search results":
   ```tsx
   {hasProject && !isLoading && !error && issues.length > 0 && filteredIssues.length === 0 && searchQuery && (
     <div className="issues-section-empty">
       No issues matching "{searchQuery}"
     </div>
   )}

   {hasProject && !isLoading && !error && issues.length === 0 && (
     <div className="issues-section-empty">
       No {filter === "all" ? "" : filter} issues found
     </div>
   )}
   ```

## CSS Changes (apps/desktop/src/components/sidebar/IssuesSection.css)

Add styles for the search row, matching the existing dark theme patterns:

```css
.issues-section-search {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 6px;
  padding: 0 2px;
  position: relative;
}

.issues-section-search-input {
  flex: 1;
  padding: 4px 8px;
  padding-right: 24px; /* space for clear button */
  font-size: 11px;
  background-color: var(--bg-secondary, #1e1e1e);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color, #3c3c3c);
  border-radius: 4px;
  color: var(--text-primary, #cccccc);
  transition: border-color 0.15s ease;
  outline: none;
}

.issues-section-search-input::placeholder {
  color: var(--text-secondary, #858585);
}

.issues-section-search-input:hover:not(:disabled) {
  border-color: var(--accent-color, #007acc);
}

.issues-section-search-input:focus {
  border-color: var(--accent-color, #007acc);
}

.issues-section-search-input:disabled {
  opacity: 0.6;
  cursor: not-allowed;
}

.issues-section-search-clear {
  position: absolute;
  right: 8px;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  width: 16px;
  height: 16px;
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  color: var(--text-secondary, #858585);
  font-size: 14px;
  line-height: 1;
  cursor: pointer;
  opacity: 0.7;
  transition: opacity 0.15s ease;
  padding: 0;
}

.issues-section-search-clear:hover {
  opacity: 1;
  color: var(--text-primary, #cccccc);
}

.issues-section-search-count {
  font-size: 10px;
  color: var(--text-secondary, #858585);
  white-space: nowrap;
  flex-shrink: 0;
}
```

Use the same CSS variable patterns (--bg-secondary, --border-color, --text-primary, --text-secondary, --accent-color) that the existing `.issues-section-filter` select uses. The search input should look visually consistent with the state filter dropdown.

Integrate the same search filter from issuesStore into the KanbanBoard so that kanban cards are also filtered by the search query.

## KanbanBoard Changes (apps/desktop/src/components/kanban/KanbanBoard.tsx)

1. Import `filterIssuesBySearch` from `../../stores/issuesStore` (or from `../../stores` if re-exported).

2. Read the search query from the issues store:
   ```typescript
   const searchQuery = useIssuesStore((s) => s.searchQuery);
   ```

3. In the existing `filteredIssues` useMemo, apply the search filter AFTER the release filter. Update the memo to chain both filters:
   ```typescript
   const filteredIssues = useMemo(() => {
     let result = issues;

     // Apply release filter
     if (releaseFilter) {
       if (releaseFilter === 'unassigned') {
         result = result.filter((issue) => !assignedIssueNumbers.has(issue.number));
       } else {
         const release = tikiReleases.find((r) => r.version === releaseFilter);
         if (release) {
           const releaseIssueNumbers = new Set(release.issues.map((i) => i.number));
           result = result.filter((issue) => releaseIssueNumbers.has(issue.number));
         }
       }
     }

     // Apply text search filter
     result = filterIssuesBySearch(result, searchQuery);

     return result;
   }, [issues, releaseFilter, tikiReleases, assignedIssueNumbers, searchQuery]);
   ```

4. Add `searchQuery` to the dependency array of the `filteredIssues` useMemo.

5. Consider the completed column: the completed column uses `recentIssues` from tikiStateStore, NOT from the filtered issues list. The search filter should also be applied to completed items. In the `columns` useMemo, when building the completed column, filter the synthetic `completedIssues` array through the same search:
   ```typescript
   if (col.id === 'completed') {
     let completedIssues = [...recentIssues]
       .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.completedAt).getTime() - new Date(a.completedAt).getTime())
       .slice(0, 8)
       .map((recent) => ({ ... }));

     // Apply search filter to completed issues too
     completedIssues = filterIssuesBySearch(completedIssues, searchQuery);

     return { ...col, issues: completedIssues };
   }
   ```
   Add `searchQuery` to the `columns` useMemo dependency array.

6. Optionally, update the "No issues loaded" hint to also account for the case where issues exist but all are filtered out by search. This is a minor UX improvement -- if `issues.length > 0` but all columns are empty due to search, you could show a message. However, since each column already shows its own empty state, this is not strictly necessary.

No CSS changes are needed for this phase since the KanbanBoard already handles empty columns gracefully with the `.kanban-column-empty` style.

## Important Notes
- The search query is shared between IssuesSection and KanbanBoard via the issuesStore. When the user types in the IssuesSection search input, both views filter simultaneously.
- The debouncing happens at the input level (in IssuesSection), so the store value `searchQuery` is already debounced by the time KanbanBoard reads it.
- The release filter and search filter are independent and compose together (AND logic).
